#!/bin/bash

#Edit variables here, find your ZeroNet/data directory
initvars()
{
#Default behavior is dependant upon script being in one dir deeper than mutes/sites/users.json. Modify if needed.
ZDATDIR=${PWD}/..
#Directory to store persistant data
WORKDIR=$(mktemp -d)
#Shred command's arguments, default -fuvz
SHRED_ARGS='-fuz'
}

parse-mutes()
{
sed -n 's@.*"\(1[A-Za-z0-9]\+\)":.*@\1@p' "${ZDATDIR}/mutes.json" 
}

assign-muted-keys()
{
for key in $(parse-mutes);
	do
	local count=$((${count:-0}+1))
	muted_keys[${count}]=${key}
done
}

get-muted-keys()
{
local stop=${#muted_keys[@]}
local count=0
while [ "${count:-0}" -le "${stop}" ];
	do
		local count=$((${count:-0}+1))
		echo ${muted_keys[${count}]}
done
}

build-file-index()
{
file_index=$(mktemp -p "${WORKDIR}")
#note the slash at the end of filter's replacement, makes sed return only non-directories.
index_filter=$(mktemp -p "${WORKDIR}")
get-muted-keys | sed 's@.\+@/&\\\//p@;$a d' > "${index_filter}"
find "${ZDATDIR}" | sed -n -f "${index_filter}" > "${file_index}"
}

shred-files()
{
#loop through file index, shredding files found at line there.
while read file; do
shred "${SHRED_ARGS}" "${file}"
if [ "$?" == 0 ]; then
shredcount=$((${shredcount:-0}+1))
echo Shredded file: "${file}"
fi
done < <(cat "${file_index}")
}

remove-dirs()
{
while read directory; do
rm -rf "${directory}"
if [ ! -d "${directory}" ]; then
rmcount=$((${rmcount:-0}+1))
echo Removed directory: "${directory}"
fi
done < <(sed -rn 's@(.*1[A-Za-z0-9]{32}).*@\1\/@p' "${file_index}" | sort | uniq)
}

does-user-confirm()
{
echo Are you sure you want to delete all muted user\'s content?
echo Affected keys:
get-muted-keys

echo Please type \'yes\' to continue, \'no\' to cancel, any other will ask again.
read -e continue

case $continue in
	yes)
		return 0
	;;
	no)
		return 1
	;;
	*)
		echo -----
		does-user-confirm
	;;
esac
}

list-dependencies()
{
cat << _EOF_
sed
shred
find
which
sort
uniq
_EOF_
}

dependency-check()
{
while read need; do
local binary=$(which $need)
if [ "${binary:-MISSING}" == "MISSING" ];
	then
		echo \'$need\' is missing, is it in your PATH?
		echo It is also possible that the \'which\' command is missing
		echo Dependencies list:
		list-dependencies
		local stop=TRUE
fi
done < <(list-dependencies)

if [ "${stop:-FALSE}" == "TRUE" ];
	then
		echo Dependencies not found, supply them in your PATH
		echo Dependency list:
		list-dependencies
		exit 1
fi
}

cleanup()
{
rm -rf "${WORKDIR}"
echo Removed temporary storage directory: \"${WORKDIR}\"
}

#Commands go here.

dependency-check

initvars

if [ "${ZDATDIR+defined}" == "defined" ]; 
	then
		if [ "${ZDATDIR}." != "${PWD}." ]; 
			then
				cd "${ZDATDIR}"
		fi
	else
	echo Can\'t continue, no such directory \"${ZDATDIR}\"
	exit 1
fi
		
if ! [ -f "${ZDATDIR}/mutes.json" ]; 
	then
		echo Cannot find mutes.json, run script in ZeroNet/data\? 1>&2
		exit 1
	else
		assign-muted-keys	
fi

#check for user confirmation first
does-user-confirm

if [ $? != 0 ]; 
	then
	cleanup
	exit
fi

echo Building file index, please be patient...
build-file-index
echo Shredding files...
shred-files
echo ${shredcount:-0} files shredded.

echo Removing directories...
remove-dirs
echo ${rmcount:-0} directories removed.

#cleanup script leftovers

cleanup

@echo off
setlocal enabledelayedexpansion

:: ZeroNet\data directory, usually ROOTDIR\..
set ROOTDIR=%CD%
set TARGDIR=%ROOTDIR%\..
set BINDIR=%ROOTDIR%\bin
set TMPDIR=%ROOTDIR%\tmp
set SHREDARGS=-fuz

::dependency check, unzipping should leave these there
for %%A IN (sed.exe shred.exe sort.exe uniq.exe libiconv2.dll regex2.dll libintl3.dll) DO (
IF NOT EXIST "%BINDIR%\%%A" (
echo %%A missing, please supply it in "%BINDIR%".
echo Dependency list:
call :dependencies
echo.
echo See README.txt for a list of sources.
echo Press any key to exit.
GOTO :EXIT
)
)

::set PATH to include deps
set PATH=%BINDIR%;%PATH%

::does mutes.json exist in ROOTDIR? if not, error out

IF NOT EXIST "%TARGDIR%\mutes.json" (
echo mutes.json not found in "%TARGDIR%". Either modify scrub.bat to have TARGDIR environment variable point to directory in which mutes.json is, or move scrub.d folder to ZeroNet\data directory.
GOTO :EXIT
)
::fallthrough means it does exist and is found, continue parsing
sed -n s@.*\^"\(1[A-Za-z0-9]\+\)\^":.*@\1@p "%TARGDIR%\mutes.json" > "%TMPDIR%\keys.tmp"

::ask user for confirmation
call :userconf
IF /I "%yorn%" == "yes" ( goto :operate )
goto :cleanup
::build the file list
:operate
echo Parsing keys...
sed "s@.\+@/&\\\\/p@;$a d" "%TMPDIR%\keys.tmp" > "%TMPDIR%\filter.tmp"
echo Finding content relating to keys, please be patient...
dir /s /b "%TARGDIR%" | sed -n -f "%TMPDIR%\filter.tmp" > "%TMPDIR%\shredlist.tmp"
::shred files
echo Shredding files; removing directories will take place after shredding.
set delcount=0
FOR /f "delims= tokens=* eol= usebackq" %%A IN (`sed -n p "%TMPDIR%\shredlist.tmp"`) DO (
shred %SHREDARGS% "%%A" 2>NUL
IF NOT ERRORLEVEL 1 ( echo Shredded file "%%A"
set /a delcount=!delcount!+1
)
)
echo.
IF DEFINED delcount (
echo %delcount% files shredded.
) ELSE ( echo 0 files shredded.)
echo.
echo Removing muted key's directories.
sed -rn "s@(.*1[A-Za-z0-9]{32}).*@\1\\@p" "%TMPDIR%\shredlist.tmp" | sort | uniq > "%TMPDIR%\rmdirlist.tmp"
FOR /f "delims= tokens=* eol= usebackq" %%A IN (`sed -n p "%TMPDIR%\rmdirlist.tmp"`) DO (
rmdir /s /q "%%A" 2>NUL 1>NUL
IF NOT EXIST "%%A" ( echo Removed directory file "%%A"
set /a rmcount=!rmcount!+1
)
)
echo.
IF DEFINED rmcount (
echo %rmcount% directories removed.
) ELSE ( echo 0 directories removed.)
echo.

:cleanup
echo Cleaning up temporary files...
del /f /q "%TMPDIR%\*"

:EOS
echo Reached end of script.
echo Press any key to exit.
:EXIT
pause 2>NUL >NUL
exit

::functions begin here

::UI to ask for confirmation
:userconf
echo Are you sure you want to delete all muted user's content?
echo 
echo Affected keys:
sed -n p "%TMPDIR%\keys.tmp"
echo.
echo Please type 'yes' to continue, 'no' to cancel, any other will ask again.

sed -n -e "/^\s*yes\s*$/I{s@^\s*@@;s@\s*$@@;p;beof};/^\s*no\s*$/I{s@^\s*@@;s@\s*$@@;p;beof};s@.*@Please type 'yes' to continue, 'no' to cancel, any other will ask again.@w /dev/stderr" -e "b;:eof;q" > "%TMPDIR%\userconf.tmp"
call :setvalf yorn "%TMPDIR%\userconf.tmp"
GOTO :EOF

:setval
FOR /f "eol= tokens=1,* delims== usebackq" %%A IN (`echo %1`) DO (
set %%A=%%B
)
GOTO :EOF

:setvalf
FOR /f "eol= tokens=* delims= usebackq" %%A IN (`sed -n p %2`) DO (
set %1=%%A
)
GOTO :EOF

::list dependencies, i miss you heredocs
:dependencies
echo sed.exe
echo shred.exe
echo sort.exe
echo uniq.exe
echo libiconv2.dll
echo regex2.dll
echo libintl3.dll
GOTO :EOF

Unzip into your ZeroNet/data directory.

Linux users: chmod 744 ./scrub-muted-users/scrub.sh && ./scrub-muted-users/scrub.sh

Windows users should run ZeroNet\data\scrub-muted-users\scrub.cmd

scrub will parse your mutes.json, assemble list of ZeroNet files owned by those users, and shred them, writing random data to their inodes until it is very difficult to recover the data from the disk. This behavior is dependent upon having a storage medium that writes data in place; platter drives do, SSDs don't. Don't use this on an SSD, it will shorten the lifespan of the disk faster than normal operation. In addition, ZeroNet writes data quite frequently; consider moving ZeroNet to a HDD or other, hardier storage medium.
